I'm seeing problems taking multiple readings from the internal VBAT and TEMP sensors on a MultiTech mDot device.  The first reading after reset is correct, then all others are not.  I have been able to fix the problem by stopping the ADC manually before every read:

            AnalogIn vBatIn(ADC_VBAT);

            // Disable the ADC before every reading to get valid values
            ADC1->CR2 &= ~ADC_CR2_ADON;   
            vBat = vBatIn.read_u16();

I've had to directly access the hardware because the AnalogIn class doesn't expose any way to modify the CR2 register.  It also doesn't implement any functionality in the class destructor.  This causes the ADC to always remain active and uses additional power.

Using mbed-os 5.4.2 with libmDot-mbed5 2.0.17-1.

The stm32f4xx has additional [states](https://github.com/ARMmbed/mbed-os/blob/master/targets/TARGET_STM/TARGET_STM32F4/device/stm32f4xx_hal_dma.h#L121) as compared to other stm32 parts.

```
/** 
  * @brief  HAL DMA State structures definition
  */
typedef enum
{
  HAL_DMA_STATE_RESET             = 0x00U,  /*!< DMA not yet initialized or disabled */
  HAL_DMA_STATE_READY             = 0x01U,  /*!< DMA initialized and ready for use   */
  HAL_DMA_STATE_READY_MEM0        = 0x11U,  /*!< DMA Mem0 process success            */ // FIX
  HAL_DMA_STATE_READY_MEM1        = 0x21U,  /*!< DMA Mem1 process success            */ // FIX
  HAL_DMA_STATE_READY_HALF_MEM0   = 0x31U,  /*!< DMA Mem0 Half process success       */ // FIX
  HAL_DMA_STATE_READY_HALF_MEM1   = 0x41U,  /*!< DMA Mem1 Half process success       */ // FIX
  HAL_DMA_STATE_BUSY              = 0x02U,  /*!< DMA process is ongoing              */
  HAL_DMA_STATE_BUSY_MEM0         = 0x12U,  /*!< DMA Mem0 process is ongoing         */ // FIX
  HAL_DMA_STATE_BUSY_MEM1         = 0x22U,  /*!< DMA Mem1 process is ongoing         */ // FIX
  HAL_DMA_STATE_TIMEOUT           = 0x03U,  /*!< DMA timeout state                   */
  HAL_DMA_STATE_ERROR             = 0x04U,  /*!< DMA error state                     */
  HAL_DMA_STATE_ABORT             = 0x05U,  /*!< DMA Abort state                     */
}HAL_DMA_StateTypeDef;
```

These state enumeration values for `HAL_DMA_STATE_READY` and `HAL_DMA_STATE_BUSY` are set up as maskable flags.

However, [stm32f4xx_hal_dma.c](https://github.com/ARMmbed/mbed-os/blob/master/targets/TARGET_STM/TARGET_STM32F4/device/stm32f4xx_hal_dma.c) assumes natural enumerations in the conditionals. For example:
```
if(hdma->State != HAL_DMA_STATE_BUSY)
  {
    hdma->ErrorCode = HAL_DMA_ERROR_NO_XFER;
    
    /* Process Unlocked */
    __HAL_UNLOCK(hdma);
    
    return HAL_ERROR;
  }
```

This introduces potential corner case issues relating to stopping, starting, init/deinit, and setting callbacks.
